1
00:00:21,789 --> 00:00:27,529
<i>( music playing )</i>

2
00:00:44,746 --> 00:00:48,482
Ann: <i>San Francisco, 1971.</i>

3
00:00:48,516 --> 00:00:52,687
<i>Thousands were marching in the streets
to demand an end to the Vietnam War.</i>

4
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:55,690
<i>Racial tensions were high
after the Hunter's Point riots.</i>

5
00:00:55,723 --> 00:00:58,492
<i>And on January 19th,</i>

6
00:00:58,526 --> 00:01:02,095
<i>two oil tankers collided
in the San Francisco Bay</i>

7
00:01:02,129 --> 00:01:07,134
<i>spilling 800,000 gallons of
crude oil into the water.</i>

8
00:01:07,167 --> 00:01:09,804
<i>Back then, there was no
plan for how to clean it up.</i>

9
00:01:09,837 --> 00:01:13,841
<i>On one side, you had the oil
company who was responsible.</i>

10
00:01:13,875 --> 00:01:18,478
<i>On the other, you had the hippies
who wanted to protect their beaches.</i>

11
00:01:18,513 --> 00:01:20,548
<i>And in the middle
were the truckers.</i>

12
00:01:20,582 --> 00:01:24,686
<i>This is the story of how that
oil spill changed my life</i>

13
00:01:24,719 --> 00:01:26,521
<i>because I was
married to a trucker</i>

14
00:01:26,554 --> 00:01:28,523
<i>named Charlie Walker.</i>

15
00:01:31,458 --> 00:01:34,127
<i>Charlie only had one
truck to his name,</i>

16
00:01:34,161 --> 00:01:36,698
<i>but he had plenty of hustle.</i>

17
00:01:36,731 --> 00:01:38,833
<i>In the days leading
up to the oil spill,</i>

18
00:01:38,866 --> 00:01:41,603
<i>the power center for all
trucking in the Bay Area</i>

19
00:01:41,636 --> 00:01:43,905
<i>was a man named Chuck Sumner.</i>

20
00:01:43,938 --> 00:01:47,575
<i>Maybe Chuck himself was
a racist. I don't know.</i>

21
00:01:47,609 --> 00:01:50,912
<i>But his dispatchers
were another story.</i>

22
00:01:50,945 --> 00:01:54,816
<i>Every day, Charlie would go down to
Chuck's worksites and try to get on a job,</i>

23
00:01:54,849 --> 00:01:57,351
<i>and every day the same
thing would happen.</i>

24
00:01:57,384 --> 00:02:00,187
Howdy, foreman. Load her up.

25
00:02:00,220 --> 00:02:03,256
- No.
- Why?

26
00:02:04,592 --> 00:02:06,728
'Cause you ain't
got no work order.

27
00:02:06,761 --> 00:02:08,495
You ain't got no
Chuck Sumner truck.

28
00:02:08,529 --> 00:02:11,566
Hell, you probably don't
even have a Class B.

29
00:02:11,599 --> 00:02:13,367
Besides, you're blocking
the goddamn line.

30
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:16,738
So if you don't haul this pile
of shit out of here right quick,

31
00:02:16,771 --> 00:02:20,140
I'm gonna hook it up
and drag it off myself.

32
00:02:27,247 --> 00:02:29,383
<i>Maybe you'd think things
would be different,</i>

33
00:02:29,416 --> 00:02:33,788
<i>this being San Francisco,
but you'd be wrong.</i>

34
00:02:33,821 --> 00:02:35,690
<i>Money was tight,</i>

35
00:02:35,723 --> 00:02:38,458
<i>and I was trying to do my
part in managing the numbers.</i>

36
00:02:40,628 --> 00:02:43,665
What the hell are you
doing? Put that jar away.

37
00:02:43,698 --> 00:02:45,399
They don't be counting
pennies for food.

38
00:02:45,432 --> 00:02:47,267
The market doesn't
care how you pay.

39
00:02:47,300 --> 00:02:49,771
Well, the neighbors
do, and I'll be damned

40
00:02:49,804 --> 00:02:52,305
if I have them passing the
basket around for us on Sundays.

41
00:02:54,509 --> 00:02:56,410
What's your pocket
money gonna do for us?

42
00:02:56,443 --> 00:02:58,913
Buy food, keep the lights on.

43
00:02:58,946 --> 00:03:02,215
- And what about next week?
- Same pocket.

44
00:03:02,249 --> 00:03:04,619
You should be laying
bricks with Willie.

45
00:03:04,652 --> 00:03:07,421
They got steady work. He
called again last night.

46
00:03:07,454 --> 00:03:09,432
Do you want to drive around
in that old rickety dump truck

47
00:03:09,456 --> 00:03:12,527
burning gas, hoping,
I don't know,

48
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:14,361
Santa Claus is gonna
fill it with dirt?

49
00:03:14,394 --> 00:03:16,564
I can't lay bricks no more.

50
00:03:16,597 --> 00:03:18,298
You can't or you won't?

51
00:03:18,331 --> 00:03:21,736
- I won't.
- Pooki, go play with your sisters.

52
00:03:26,808 --> 00:03:28,810
You're gonna have to decide.

53
00:03:28,843 --> 00:03:31,311
You gonna keep dreaming
about being your own boss

54
00:03:31,344 --> 00:03:34,682
or lay bricks to
feed your family?

55
00:03:34,716 --> 00:03:38,452
We lose this house in February
if you don't find work.

56
00:03:38,485 --> 00:03:41,956
Listen, baby, if I
thought laying bricks

57
00:03:41,989 --> 00:03:45,927
would make me a foreman
someday, I'd be first in line,

58
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:47,662
but there is no such thing

59
00:03:47,695 --> 00:03:50,464
as a Black brick laying foreman.

60
00:03:50,497 --> 00:03:52,700
Now, that truck is
the only thing we got.

61
00:03:52,734 --> 00:03:56,771
Well, maybe come February we
should all live in the truck then.

62
00:03:56,804 --> 00:03:59,607
I told you, I'm not
tearing my goddamn hands up

63
00:03:59,640 --> 00:04:02,777
doing that brick laying
bullshit no more.

64
00:04:05,947 --> 00:04:07,915
Buy some gloves.

65
00:04:16,389 --> 00:04:19,861
<i>Instead of buying gloves,
Charlie doubled down,</i>

66
00:04:19,894 --> 00:04:22,429
<i>decided the only way
to get what he wanted</i>

67
00:04:22,462 --> 00:04:24,699
<i>was to make even more
trouble for Chuck Sumner.</i>

68
00:04:24,732 --> 00:04:26,634
<i>Thought maybe if he
made enough trouble,</i>

69
00:04:26,667 --> 00:04:29,804
<i>eventually Chuck would have
to start paying attention.</i>

70
00:04:31,806 --> 00:04:34,909
We moved the drop-off to
Third and King Street.

71
00:04:34,942 --> 00:04:36,409
Sure thing, boss.

72
00:04:37,879 --> 00:04:41,015
All right. That's it.

73
00:04:41,048 --> 00:04:43,851
Hey, get going,
Willie. It's on.

74
00:04:46,554 --> 00:04:49,724
- ( radio chatter )
- That's right. Negro.

75
00:04:49,757 --> 00:04:52,894
Not "hero." I said "Negro."

76
00:04:52,927 --> 00:04:55,997
I got a Black Panther son of
a bitch blocking my trucks.

77
00:04:56,030 --> 00:05:00,034
( radio chatter continues )

78
00:05:00,067 --> 00:05:03,538
No, goddamn it.
There's a Black man!

79
00:05:03,571 --> 00:05:06,373
Man on radio: <i>He don't
have no sand loader,</i>

80
00:05:06,406 --> 00:05:08,543
<i>but he says we can get
one over here for you.</i>

81
00:05:12,713 --> 00:05:16,851
You know what? I am one of those uppity
Negros looking to crash the party.

82
00:05:20,855 --> 00:05:23,758
- Merry Christmas.
- Shit!

83
00:05:29,462 --> 00:05:31,464
I'm gonna whip your ass, boy!

84
00:05:35,670 --> 00:05:37,839
Ann: <i>Charlie just
wanted a fair shake,</i>

85
00:05:37,872 --> 00:05:40,641
<i>a chance to have
something of his own,</i>

86
00:05:40,675 --> 00:05:42,442
- <i>to be his own boss.</i>
- ( siren wailing )

87
00:05:42,475 --> 00:05:46,379
<i>It wasn't about race for him,</i>

88
00:05:46,413 --> 00:05:50,017
<i>but for everyone else,
it was always about race.</i>

89
00:05:53,588 --> 00:05:55,022
Step out of the cab.

90
00:05:58,860 --> 00:06:00,962
Charlie: What the hell?

91
00:06:00,995 --> 00:06:03,463
You know, it is hard to
find good help these days?

92
00:06:03,496 --> 00:06:05,465
I just dropped my
worker Willie off,

93
00:06:05,498 --> 00:06:08,102
and I say, "Willie, make sure you
untie the banner from the truck."

94
00:06:08,135 --> 00:06:10,104
And I'll be damned.

95
00:06:10,137 --> 00:06:13,608
They say if you want something done
right, you gotta do it yourself.

96
00:06:13,641 --> 00:06:16,611
- I'll take care of it.
- Don't you move.

97
00:06:16,644 --> 00:06:18,478
Hey, man, that's not necessary.

98
00:06:18,512 --> 00:06:20,548
I said I'll take
care of it. Be cool.

99
00:06:20,581 --> 00:06:22,717
You don't take direction
very well, do you?

100
00:06:22,750 --> 00:06:24,819
Now turn around and
face the vehicle.

101
00:06:26,921 --> 00:06:29,389
Old cracker-ass cracker.

102
00:06:39,166 --> 00:06:42,503
<i>Charlie got 30 days, but
Chuck Sumner got tired</i>

103
00:06:42,536 --> 00:06:44,906
<i>of having Charlie be
a thorn in his side,</i>

104
00:06:44,939 --> 00:06:46,774
<i>gave him a contract,</i>

105
00:06:46,807 --> 00:06:49,644
<i>put him in charge of
all the Black truckers.</i>

106
00:06:49,677 --> 00:06:53,915
<i>Suddenly, on our side of
town, Charlie was the man.</i>

107
00:06:55,182 --> 00:06:56,851
<i>And that's when it happened.</i>

108
00:06:56,884 --> 00:06:59,120
<i>Charlie was driving home,</i>

109
00:06:59,153 --> 00:07:00,697
<i>saw a line of trucks
heading to the beach</i>

110
00:07:00,721 --> 00:07:01,923
<i>in the middle of the night.</i>

111
00:07:01,956 --> 00:07:03,066
Woman on radio: <i>The
police are here.</i>

112
00:07:03,090 --> 00:07:04,692
<i>There's trucks everywhere.</i>

113
00:07:04,725 --> 00:07:06,069
Ann: <i>He didn't know
about the oil spill yet,</i>

114
00:07:06,093 --> 00:07:07,395
<i>but he knew something was up.</i>

115
00:07:07,427 --> 00:07:09,797
Man on radio: <i>We have a
report that a large ship hit</i>

116
00:07:09,830 --> 00:07:12,199
<i>the Golden Gate Bridge just
after midnight tonight.</i>

117
00:07:12,233 --> 00:07:14,802
Ann: <i>Decided he had to
follow those trucks.</i>

118
00:07:14,835 --> 00:07:18,039
Street's closed. You can't get
through. You gotta go left.

119
00:07:18,072 --> 00:07:21,542
Those six trucks ahead are
mine. Charlie Walker Trucking.

120
00:07:21,575 --> 00:07:22,910
I gotta stay with my trucks.

121
00:07:22,944 --> 00:07:24,254
Yeah, and I'm the
chief of police.

122
00:07:24,278 --> 00:07:26,714
Get out of the
line and turn left.

123
00:07:26,747 --> 00:07:30,518
Ask the guy behind me.
Please, go ahead. Ask him.

124
00:07:30,551 --> 00:07:34,555
Look, officer, you're holding them up
too. Those are Chuck Sumner trucks.

125
00:07:34,588 --> 00:07:36,057
Behind those are
Mike Folgers trucks.

126
00:07:36,090 --> 00:07:38,259
Behind those are the
damn National Guard.

127
00:07:38,292 --> 00:07:40,561
Now are you gonna hold this
line up because I'm Black

128
00:07:40,594 --> 00:07:41,805
or are you gonna keep
this train rolling?

129
00:07:41,829 --> 00:07:44,899
All right, get out of here.

130
00:07:44,932 --> 00:07:46,843
Woman on radio: <i>Every truck and
loader within a 50-mile radius</i>

131
00:07:46,867 --> 00:07:48,569
<i>is headed to the coastline.</i>

132
00:07:48,602 --> 00:07:50,071
Ann: <i>Charlie
followed those trucks</i>

133
00:07:50,104 --> 00:07:51,973
<i>all the way down to the beach.</i>

134
00:07:52,006 --> 00:07:54,842
<i>And when he got there,
guess who he found.</i>

135
00:07:54,875 --> 00:07:56,978
<i>Chuck Sumner himself.</i>

136
00:07:57,011 --> 00:07:58,746
What the hell's
going on here, Chuck?

137
00:07:58,779 --> 00:08:01,215
You got half your trucks on
this beach, so what gives?

138
00:08:01,248 --> 00:08:04,085
We're cleaning up the million some
odd barrels of crude washing up.

139
00:08:04,118 --> 00:08:06,120
Hot damn! When did it happen?

140
00:08:06,153 --> 00:08:08,823
Midnight. Broke
the ship in half.

141
00:08:08,856 --> 00:08:10,992
So you got the call,
Folgers got the call,

142
00:08:11,025 --> 00:08:12,669
but nobody bother to give
old Charlie Walker a shot?

143
00:08:12,693 --> 00:08:14,862
Look, goddamn it, what
am I supposed to do,

144
00:08:14,895 --> 00:08:16,630
call every bar in San Francisco

145
00:08:16,664 --> 00:08:18,308
until I find the one that
you're getting drunk in?

146
00:08:18,332 --> 00:08:21,802
If you want in, I
suggest you hop in

147
00:08:21,836 --> 00:08:24,105
that new Cadillac of yours
and hightail your ass

148
00:08:24,138 --> 00:08:25,773
up to the Long
Wharf in Richmond.

149
00:08:25,806 --> 00:08:28,109
- Richmond?
- Every contractor around

150
00:08:28,142 --> 00:08:30,244
is bidding for a piece of
this right now, except you.

151
00:08:30,277 --> 00:08:32,889
Don't send me over there just to
get me off your ass now. I want in.

152
00:08:32,913 --> 00:08:36,250
Look, my hands are tied
right now. Just... here.

153
00:08:36,283 --> 00:08:40,621
- Go see Mike Marshall. He's the oil man in charge.
- Mike Marshall.

154
00:08:40,654 --> 00:08:42,623
Oh, Charlie, you think
about pulling any shit

155
00:08:42,656 --> 00:08:44,134
like that billboard
stunt in the Mission,

156
00:08:44,158 --> 00:08:46,227
and they'll have your
ass in a sling for good.

157
00:08:46,260 --> 00:08:50,197
This is Tower Oil. They're
already integrated.

158
00:08:56,003 --> 00:08:59,040
All: Tower Oil
out! Tower Oil out!

159
00:08:59,073 --> 00:09:03,811
Ann: <i>By sunup, the hippies were
already out protesting the spill.</i>

160
00:09:03,844 --> 00:09:05,813
<i>Charlie didn't have
to worry about them,</i>

161
00:09:05,846 --> 00:09:08,149
<i>but he knew Tower Oil
wouldn't just let him in.</i>

162
00:09:08,182 --> 00:09:12,286
<i>Just to get in line, he had to
use every trick in the book.</i>

163
00:09:12,319 --> 00:09:17,058
Yo, hold it up!
Hold it up! Stop.

164
00:09:20,194 --> 00:09:21,796
Didn't you see the sign?

165
00:09:23,097 --> 00:09:25,933
What's the matter,
boy? Can't you read?

166
00:09:29,036 --> 00:09:32,606
- What's your name, officer?
- What did you say to me?

167
00:09:32,640 --> 00:09:38,212
I said, "What's your fucking name,
off-ic-er?" Don't you speak English?

168
00:09:38,245 --> 00:09:41,682
I don't think you understand
what's going on here, son.

169
00:09:41,715 --> 00:09:43,284
See, this is private property.

170
00:09:43,317 --> 00:09:46,329
Now you're gonna have to back this piece
of shit up and move it on out of here.

171
00:09:46,353 --> 00:09:49,190
Look, damn it, I work for
Tower Oil in Los Angeles.

172
00:09:49,223 --> 00:09:53,027
I'm the superintendent in charge of
contamination for the entire North Coast.

173
00:09:53,060 --> 00:09:55,329
Yeah, well, this ain't
Los "Ang-geh-lees."

174
00:09:55,362 --> 00:09:58,065
I don't need this shit. Give
me your name and badge number

175
00:09:58,099 --> 00:09:59,342
so I can report
this to Marshall.

176
00:09:59,366 --> 00:10:02,369
- Marshall?
- Name, badge number.

177
00:10:02,403 --> 00:10:05,206
You know Mike Marshall?

178
00:10:05,239 --> 00:10:09,110
Mike Marshall, white
dude, about yay tall,

179
00:10:09,143 --> 00:10:12,012
bosses peckerwoods like
you around for a living.

180
00:10:14,882 --> 00:10:17,051
- You gotta understand, um...
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

181
00:10:17,084 --> 00:10:19,062
- We don't get many, uh...
- Still ain't no excuse.

182
00:10:19,086 --> 00:10:22,123
No. I'm sorry about this, sir.

183
00:10:22,156 --> 00:10:25,893
Now what did you say
your name was again?

184
00:10:25,926 --> 00:10:28,729
Man: Look, fellas, we're gonna
need every truck we can muster.

185
00:10:28,762 --> 00:10:31,065
We got small areas,
but a lot of them.

186
00:10:31,098 --> 00:10:33,901
Look about, boys,
I got me a beast.

187
00:10:38,038 --> 00:10:39,382
Some of you are gonna
have to pair up,

188
00:10:39,406 --> 00:10:41,375
but do not worry
about the money.

189
00:10:41,408 --> 00:10:45,212
Every contractor's gonna get his
own purchase order with an open end.

190
00:10:45,246 --> 00:10:47,248
- All: Yeah!
- Now at the end of the day,

191
00:10:47,281 --> 00:10:50,384
a Tower Oil rep is gonna
sign off on your invoices,

192
00:10:50,417 --> 00:10:54,922
but we need some kind
of billing every day.

193
00:10:54,955 --> 00:10:58,325
Now if there are any problems,
feel free to call me.

194
00:10:59,827 --> 00:11:01,896
All right, Half Moon Bay.

195
00:11:01,929 --> 00:11:03,406
Who can work the beach
at Half Moon Bay?

196
00:11:03,430 --> 00:11:06,167
All right, you, you, and you.

197
00:11:09,203 --> 00:11:12,773
Uh, San Mateo. Red, that's
your neck of the woods.

198
00:11:12,806 --> 00:11:15,809
You take San Mateo and take
two other guys from this group.

199
00:11:17,811 --> 00:11:20,781
Well, I'll be a monkey's uncle.

200
00:11:20,814 --> 00:11:25,252
Why, that doesn't surprise
me. Now I see the resemblance.

201
00:11:25,286 --> 00:11:29,823
You owe me a construction tower,
boy, and I'm gonna get it.

202
00:11:32,059 --> 00:11:34,962
You and you, let's go work.

203
00:11:34,995 --> 00:11:37,331
Haines: Stinson
Beach, Marin County.

204
00:11:37,364 --> 00:11:40,301
One way in, one way out.

205
00:11:40,334 --> 00:11:43,871
We only need a small
crew, one or two trucks.

206
00:11:43,904 --> 00:11:47,808
- Come on, anybody.
- Nah, no way. I ain't gonna do that.

207
00:11:47,841 --> 00:11:49,343
Stinson Beach, guys.

208
00:11:49,376 --> 00:11:51,245
Here. Right here.
I'll take it.

209
00:11:52,246 --> 00:11:54,815
Come on, anybody!

210
00:11:54,848 --> 00:11:57,284
You're gonna get a truck
in or out of there.

211
00:11:57,318 --> 00:12:00,988
Why don't you integrate
and give a brother a job?

212
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:08,495
- Name?
- Charlie Walker.

213
00:12:08,530 --> 00:12:09,964
Company name.

214
00:12:09,997 --> 00:12:12,499
Oh, Charlie Walker Trucking.

215
00:12:12,534 --> 00:12:15,035
This is gonna take three
trucks. You got that many?

216
00:12:15,069 --> 00:12:18,305
- No, but I'll get them.
- Fine.

217
00:12:18,339 --> 00:12:21,008
- You'll make it work.
- Yes, sir.

218
00:12:21,041 --> 00:12:23,844
I work with Chuck Sumner Trucking
too. I'll get the rest form him.

219
00:12:23,877 --> 00:12:26,981
With this blank purchase order,
you can get anything you need.

220
00:12:27,014 --> 00:12:29,183
Now we're not concerned
about the money right now.

221
00:12:29,216 --> 00:12:31,852
Just get that damn
oil off the beach,

222
00:12:31,885 --> 00:12:33,463
you understand what
I'm saying to you, son?

223
00:12:33,487 --> 00:12:35,089
Yes, sir.

224
00:12:35,122 --> 00:12:36,890
Get the damn oil off
the beach. I got it.

225
00:12:44,164 --> 00:12:45,766
Thank you, sir.

226
00:12:56,443 --> 00:12:59,446
( ringing )

227
00:13:05,185 --> 00:13:06,420
Is this the police?

228
00:13:06,453 --> 00:13:08,889
No, this ain't the police!

229
00:13:08,922 --> 00:13:10,300
Baby, you'll never guess
what just happened.

230
00:13:10,324 --> 00:13:12,960
Charlie Walker, do you
know what time it is?

231
00:13:12,993 --> 00:13:15,129
Of course I know
what time it is.

232
00:13:15,162 --> 00:13:16,430
What time is it?

233
00:13:16,463 --> 00:13:20,234
It's 6:00 in the damn morning.

234
00:13:20,267 --> 00:13:22,537
Baby, baby, we gonna be rich.

235
00:13:22,570 --> 00:13:24,905
We gonna pay off the house.
We gonna buy another truck.

236
00:13:24,938 --> 00:13:28,242
I got another hour before I gotta
get the girls dressed for school,

237
00:13:28,275 --> 00:13:30,911
and you're calling me
at 6 in the morning

238
00:13:30,944 --> 00:13:33,447
after you've been
out all night again?

239
00:13:33,480 --> 00:13:34,516
Bye!

240
00:13:37,184 --> 00:13:38,218
Bye.

241
00:13:40,454 --> 00:13:42,423
Ann: <i>Now, the oil company
was hiring truckers</i>

242
00:13:42,456 --> 00:13:45,092
<i>like Charlie to
take the oil away,</i>

243
00:13:45,125 --> 00:13:47,094
<i>but who was gonna get
it off the beaches</i>

244
00:13:47,127 --> 00:13:49,196
<i>and into the trucks
in the first place?</i>

245
00:13:49,229 --> 00:13:51,566
<i>For that they decided
to work with the people</i>

246
00:13:51,599 --> 00:13:54,401
<i>who were already out
there doing it for free,</i>

247
00:13:54,435 --> 00:13:56,437
<i>the hippies.</i>

248
00:13:56,470 --> 00:13:59,340
<i>But it wasn't exactly
a match made in heaven.</i>

249
00:14:03,611 --> 00:14:05,446
Sorry to interrupt
you, Mr. Bennett,

250
00:14:05,479 --> 00:14:07,615
but I have the contract
reports you asked for.

251
00:14:07,649 --> 00:14:12,119
Why don't you save me the read
and just give me the high points?

252
00:14:12,152 --> 00:14:14,288
Do we have enough
boots on the ground?

253
00:14:14,321 --> 00:14:19,893
- I think so.
- Wow, VP of Tower Oil San Francisco office

254
00:14:19,927 --> 00:14:22,396
has just assured me
that he thinks so.

255
00:14:22,429 --> 00:14:23,964
I mean, yes, we do.

256
00:14:23,997 --> 00:14:25,600
We have every truck,
loader, and operator

257
00:14:25,633 --> 00:14:27,468
in the Bay Area under contract.

258
00:14:27,502 --> 00:14:28,969
So we're doing
everything we can.

259
00:14:29,002 --> 00:14:30,648
You still haven't answered
my question, Walter.

260
00:14:30,672 --> 00:14:32,607
It's the volunteers, sir.

261
00:14:32,640 --> 00:14:35,409
As long as the volunteers
stay onboard, we can keep up.

262
00:14:35,442 --> 00:14:38,646
This whole thing hinges on a
bunch of hippie war protestors?

263
00:14:38,680 --> 00:14:41,982
- Volunteers, sir.
- Fine.

264
00:14:42,015 --> 00:14:44,519
Then just keep
them volunteering.

265
00:14:44,552 --> 00:14:46,153
Walter: That's
the tricky part.

266
00:14:46,186 --> 00:14:49,323
Most of these people were protestors a
week ago, and we can't get near them.

267
00:14:49,356 --> 00:14:51,992
They can't be protesting

268
00:14:52,025 --> 00:14:53,460
and helping at the same time.

269
00:14:53,494 --> 00:14:56,029
- Which is it?
- It's a mess, sir.

270
00:14:58,332 --> 00:15:03,003
Walter, you know the
difference between a hippie

271
00:15:03,036 --> 00:15:07,675
and a couple of corporate
assholes like you and me?

272
00:15:07,709 --> 00:15:10,177
No, sir.

273
00:15:11,278 --> 00:15:14,348
- Credit cards.
- Credit cards?

274
00:15:14,381 --> 00:15:16,417
Yeah, a steady paycheck,

275
00:15:16,450 --> 00:15:20,655
consumer debt, dental coverage,

276
00:15:20,688 --> 00:15:23,357
paid sick leave, and
as many free pens

277
00:15:23,390 --> 00:15:26,360
and pencils as they can steal.

278
00:15:26,393 --> 00:15:27,633
You understand what I'm saying?

279
00:15:29,396 --> 00:15:32,600
- Yes.
- Pay them.

280
00:15:34,401 --> 00:15:36,036
Give them money.

281
00:15:36,069 --> 00:15:37,681
I don't care if you have
to sneak up behind them

282
00:15:37,705 --> 00:15:40,174
and stuff twenties
in their pockets.

283
00:15:41,709 --> 00:15:43,611
Get them sucking on the teat.

284
00:15:43,645 --> 00:15:44,685
I'll take care of it, sir.

285
00:15:44,712 --> 00:15:49,551
And, Sharpe, money is no object.

286
00:15:49,584 --> 00:15:52,052
Yes, sir. Understood.

287
00:15:54,021 --> 00:15:56,524
Man on radio: <i>At approximately
1:42 this morning,</i>

288
00:15:56,558 --> 00:16:00,060
<i>two Tower Oil tankers collided just
east of the Golden Gate Bridge.</i>

289
00:16:00,093 --> 00:16:02,062
Ann: <i>Stinson Beach,
where Charlie was headed,</i>

290
00:16:02,095 --> 00:16:04,064
<i>is up north of the Golden Gate.</i>

291
00:16:04,097 --> 00:16:06,701
<i>It was hard to get
to, and nobody thought</i>

292
00:16:06,734 --> 00:16:09,504
<i>it was gonna be a big
job, but for Charlie,</i>

293
00:16:09,537 --> 00:16:13,073
<i>it was an opportunity to show
the world what he could do.</i>

294
00:16:13,106 --> 00:16:16,109
( phone ringing )

295
00:16:20,748 --> 00:16:24,586
Yes. Yes, sir. Mr. Sharpe
is working on that.

296
00:16:24,619 --> 00:16:27,421
Yes, we're getting more
volunteers all the time.

297
00:16:27,454 --> 00:16:29,094
Tell them we're gonna
need more hay bales.

298
00:16:29,122 --> 00:16:31,726
Woman: I did. We have another
nine or ten on the way.

299
00:16:31,759 --> 00:16:34,328
Yes, sir. They're working.

300
00:16:34,361 --> 00:16:36,997
Um, all we have are
volunteers at the moment.

301
00:16:39,066 --> 00:16:43,136
( squeaking )

302
00:16:47,140 --> 00:16:48,610
Hay bales don't soak up oil.

303
00:16:48,643 --> 00:16:50,645
You're just making
a bigger mess.

304
00:16:50,678 --> 00:16:52,747
- May I help you?
- Yes.

305
00:16:52,780 --> 00:16:57,251
Can I get a cheeseburger on
white bread with extra mayo?

306
00:16:57,284 --> 00:16:59,253
- And a vanilla shake?
- Excuse me.

307
00:16:59,286 --> 00:17:00,622
We're a little busy right now.

308
00:17:00,655 --> 00:17:03,625
If you wanna help,
the beach is that way.

309
00:17:03,658 --> 00:17:05,636
You might want to get out of
those fancy clothes first.

310
00:17:05,660 --> 00:17:08,563
I'm the contractor who's
gonna clean up that mess.

311
00:17:08,596 --> 00:17:13,133
- You're the who?
- I'm Charlie Walker. Nice to meet you.

312
00:17:13,166 --> 00:17:16,571
- You're Mr. Walker?
- One and only.

313
00:17:17,672 --> 00:17:19,574
Ah, okay. Wait right here.

314
00:17:19,607 --> 00:17:22,075
Let me let them know that
you're here. Wait right there.

315
00:17:26,146 --> 00:17:28,716
( phone ringing )

316
00:17:36,724 --> 00:17:40,294
Ann: <i>You ever heard that
expression, "the winds of change"?</i>

317
00:17:40,327 --> 00:17:43,096
<i>Well, that's what was
about to happen to Charlie.</i>

318
00:17:43,130 --> 00:17:47,502
<i>Mother Nature decided to surprise
everybody and blow most of that oil</i>

319
00:17:47,535 --> 00:17:49,303
<i>straight past
those other beaches</i>

320
00:17:49,336 --> 00:17:52,239
<i>and all the way up to Stinson.</i>

321
00:17:52,272 --> 00:17:54,509
<i>Tower Oil probably
would've replaced Charlie</i>

322
00:17:54,542 --> 00:17:56,310
<i>with one of those
white truckers,</i>

323
00:17:56,343 --> 00:17:58,312
<i>but he was one step ahead.</i>

324
00:17:58,345 --> 00:18:00,180
<i>By the time they got there,</i>

325
00:18:00,213 --> 00:18:03,518
<i>he'd already gotten himself
in front of the cameras.</i>

326
00:18:03,551 --> 00:18:05,687
I'm going to do
whatever it takes

327
00:18:05,720 --> 00:18:07,822
to get every bit of oil
off this beautiful beach

328
00:18:07,855 --> 00:18:09,624
and out of every
ravine and inlet.

329
00:18:09,657 --> 00:18:11,859
In fact, this beach will
be in better condition

330
00:18:11,893 --> 00:18:13,895
when I leave than
it's ever been before.

331
00:18:13,928 --> 00:18:15,830
We consider ourselves
lucky to have someone

332
00:18:15,863 --> 00:18:18,566
of Mr. Walker's experience
out here on such short notice.

333
00:18:18,600 --> 00:18:21,201
- Now step aside. Move aside.
- We have little time to spare.

334
00:18:21,234 --> 00:18:23,547
I need to get out there immediately
and survey what we're up against.

335
00:18:23,571 --> 00:18:27,875
Right this way, Mr. Walker.
Nicely done in there.

336
00:18:27,909 --> 00:18:29,611
Well, those people I can handle.

337
00:18:29,644 --> 00:18:32,446
It's you all that concerns me.

338
00:18:32,479 --> 00:18:37,417
- How's that?
- Well, see, there's a small matter of me being, um...

339
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:39,754
Black.

340
00:18:39,787 --> 00:18:41,656
I hadn't noticed.

341
00:18:43,390 --> 00:18:45,492
I like the way you do
things, Mr. Sharpe.

342
00:18:45,526 --> 00:18:49,631
Let's hope I come to share those
same feelings for you, Mr. Walker.

343
00:18:52,967 --> 00:18:55,937
Yeah, we initially thought this
area was going to be contained.

344
00:18:55,970 --> 00:18:59,339
- But you were wrong.
- But we were wrong.

345
00:18:59,373 --> 00:19:02,744
Winds do change. Bite
you in the ass sometimes.

346
00:19:02,777 --> 00:19:04,444
Can we count on you, Charlie?

347
00:19:07,548 --> 00:19:10,752
Well, it will have to
be taken out by hand.

348
00:19:10,785 --> 00:19:14,589
Maybe we could take the tainted
materials and move it to a holding area.

349
00:19:14,622 --> 00:19:17,391
- That might work.
- Might work.

350
00:19:17,424 --> 00:19:19,268
I'll get you those trucks.
What else you gonna need?

351
00:19:19,292 --> 00:19:22,664
A drink, a phone,

352
00:19:22,697 --> 00:19:24,508
and I think I'll get old
Chuck Sumner on the phone

353
00:19:24,532 --> 00:19:26,266
and see if I can get
some more trucks.

354
00:19:26,299 --> 00:19:28,670
All right, let's get
you back to base camp.

355
00:19:35,442 --> 00:19:38,680
To hell with the suit, Charlie!
We'll buy you a new one.

356
00:19:43,685 --> 00:19:45,887
By the way, you're staying
at the Stinson Beach Motel.

357
00:19:45,920 --> 00:19:49,389
We've rented the entire building
out for Tower employees.

358
00:19:49,423 --> 00:19:53,293
So don't bother punching out and or
going home at the end of the night.

359
00:19:53,326 --> 00:19:55,797
This is a full-time
job. You live here now.

360
00:19:55,830 --> 00:19:59,801
- I'm gonna need two rooms.
- Money is no object.

361
00:19:59,834 --> 00:20:01,869
You know, everybody
keeps saying that,

362
00:20:01,903 --> 00:20:03,805
but I have yet to see any of it.

363
00:20:03,838 --> 00:20:06,507
I'm beginning to think it
is no object after all.

364
00:20:08,743 --> 00:20:11,445
Here's 25,000, petty cash.

365
00:20:11,478 --> 00:20:13,648
It'll get you through
tonight and tomorrow.

366
00:20:13,681 --> 00:20:15,950
- Thanks.
- You've met Dan Wallace.

367
00:20:15,983 --> 00:20:18,653
He'll handle all our force accounts.
He'll take care of everything.

368
00:20:18,686 --> 00:20:21,455
Money, personnel,
and everything.

369
00:20:21,488 --> 00:20:23,734
Without the trucks, all we can do
is mix with the locals for now.

370
00:20:23,758 --> 00:20:27,494
The cavalry's on the way,
Charlie. Don't let us down.

371
00:20:34,001 --> 00:20:36,838
Reporter: <i>came under heavy ground
fire in the Song Ve valley.</i>

372
00:20:36,871 --> 00:20:39,741
<i>( TV chatter continues )</i>

373
00:20:44,879 --> 00:20:47,849
<i>( gunfire on TV )</i>

374
00:20:47,882 --> 00:20:51,384
Ann: <i>Charlie had been in the military
right when they were integrating,</i>

375
00:20:51,418 --> 00:20:53,353
<i>so he understood that survival</i>

376
00:20:53,386 --> 00:20:55,757
<i>wasn't just about
fighting the enemy.</i>

377
00:20:55,790 --> 00:20:59,359
<i>Sometimes you had to keep
an eye on your friends too.</i>

378
00:20:59,392 --> 00:21:00,995
<i>If the oil guys were smart,</i>

379
00:21:01,028 --> 00:21:03,998
<i>Charlie would just have
to be even smarter.</i>

380
00:21:04,031 --> 00:21:05,900
<i>And with all that oil coming in</i>

381
00:21:05,933 --> 00:21:08,002
<i>and no plan for how to stop it,</i>

382
00:21:08,035 --> 00:21:12,640
<i>he was gonna have to start
getting creative pretty fast.</i>

383
00:21:12,673 --> 00:21:15,943
<i>And he was gonna need all the
friends on the ground he could get.</i>

384
00:21:24,018 --> 00:21:25,452
What's going on?

385
00:21:25,485 --> 00:21:27,789
Woman: Some guys
beat up an oil man.

386
00:21:27,822 --> 00:21:31,526
- Oil man?
- Yeah, some suit got beat up.

387
00:21:32,560 --> 00:21:33,795
All right.

388
00:21:38,431 --> 00:21:41,502
- What's going down, fellas?
- Looks like that dude was in a hatchet fight

389
00:21:41,536 --> 00:21:43,046
and was the only one
without their hatchet.

390
00:21:43,070 --> 00:21:45,940
Must've slipped and
fell real bad, ya dig?

391
00:21:45,973 --> 00:21:48,743
Oh, I dig. But if any of
you try to rat pack me,

392
00:21:48,776 --> 00:21:51,679
somebody's going to
the morgue, do you dig?

393
00:21:51,712 --> 00:21:53,881
Got no beef with you, man.

394
00:21:53,915 --> 00:21:58,553
Fuck that puppet and his
corporate puppet master.

395
00:21:58,586 --> 00:22:01,956
He's one of my puppets.
So what can I do for you?

396
00:22:01,989 --> 00:22:05,993
You have my full attention.
How can I help you?

397
00:22:06,027 --> 00:22:09,564
- You can't be the boss.
- Why? 'Cause I'm Black?

398
00:22:09,597 --> 00:22:12,477
Or because you can't find your own
asshole with a mirror and a long stick?

399
00:22:13,801 --> 00:22:16,070
You're not the boss.

400
00:22:16,103 --> 00:22:18,573
Fine. Follow me.

401
00:22:18,606 --> 00:22:20,842
And bring your hippie
commune with you.

402
00:22:22,577 --> 00:22:24,946
Why, hello, Mr. Walker.
I have a packet for you.

403
00:22:24,979 --> 00:22:27,715
You've met Mr. Sharpe.
This is Mr. Bennett.

404
00:22:27,748 --> 00:22:30,084
He's the president of
Tower Oil, and he came here

405
00:22:30,117 --> 00:22:32,553
to meet you personally
to discuss your approach.

406
00:22:32,587 --> 00:22:34,722
Welcome, Mr. Bennett.
Good to meet you, sir.

407
00:22:34,755 --> 00:22:38,793
You too, Charlie. Now that we're
all pals, what's your plan?

408
00:22:38,826 --> 00:22:42,830
Well, we have a three-mile stretch
of beach, all of which is infected.

409
00:22:42,864 --> 00:22:45,733
We're using loaders to take off
the top layer, but it's slow going.

410
00:22:45,766 --> 00:22:48,468
Honestly, we're just
moving shit around.

411
00:22:52,173 --> 00:22:55,475
I mean, the tainted material.

412
00:22:55,509 --> 00:22:58,546
Same problem at Ocean
Beach and Half Moon Bay.

413
00:22:58,579 --> 00:23:01,048
We just got back from there
and it's a fucking mess.

414
00:23:03,918 --> 00:23:08,122
We'll manage, but our biggest
threat is in the Bolinas Lagoon.

415
00:23:08,155 --> 00:23:11,058
If the oil gets in there, we'll
be here for the next three years.

416
00:23:11,092 --> 00:23:13,961
Now what are we
doing about that?

417
00:23:13,995 --> 00:23:18,065
- Some locals are putting together an oil boom.
- Out of what?

418
00:23:18,099 --> 00:23:20,001
Well, anything they
get their hands on.

419
00:23:20,034 --> 00:23:22,837
They're using logs,
fishing nets, hay.

420
00:23:22,870 --> 00:23:25,006
We build them in series,
so there's a gap.

421
00:23:25,039 --> 00:23:27,718
Then we use local boats to drag it
to the beach. Then we haul it off.

422
00:23:27,742 --> 00:23:31,444
- Is it working?
- Yes, sir. For now.

423
00:23:31,478 --> 00:23:34,447
Nice work, Charlie. We're
gonna leave Dan here.

424
00:23:34,481 --> 00:23:36,517
You're coming with
us to Candlestick.

425
00:23:36,550 --> 00:23:39,153
Maybe you can share some of your
ideas with the other guys, huh?

426
00:23:39,186 --> 00:23:43,991
Mr. Wallace, move most of the
equipment up north to the inlet.

427
00:23:44,025 --> 00:23:45,569
They're gonna need some
relief with the boom work.

428
00:23:45,593 --> 00:23:46,661
Yes, sir. I'm on it.

429
00:23:46,694 --> 00:23:48,729
And who are these good folks?

430
00:23:48,763 --> 00:23:51,933
Oh, they're heading up
the volunteer effort.

431
00:23:51,966 --> 00:23:56,804
They're good kids.
Real go-getters.

432
00:23:56,837 --> 00:24:02,910
Great. Well, we'll come back in a
couple days to get acquainted with them.

433
00:24:02,944 --> 00:24:05,212
Let's get going, guys, huh?

434
00:24:20,061 --> 00:24:22,897
<i>Charlie had bought
himself a little time,</i>

435
00:24:22,930 --> 00:24:25,066
<i>but he knew it
wouldn't be enough.</i>

436
00:24:25,099 --> 00:24:27,201
<i>He needed to think fast,</i>

437
00:24:27,234 --> 00:24:29,971
<i>so he did what he
always did best.</i>

438
00:24:30,004 --> 00:24:32,173
<i>He improvised.</i>

439
00:24:34,108 --> 00:24:37,511
- Who's using those?
- Using what?

440
00:24:37,545 --> 00:24:39,847
Skip loaders. The
paddle scrapers.

441
00:24:39,880 --> 00:24:42,817
No one. They were in the way,
so we parked them out here.

442
00:24:42,850 --> 00:24:44,585
- I want them.
- For what?

443
00:24:44,618 --> 00:24:46,187
I just want them.

444
00:24:46,220 --> 00:24:48,689
Can we get them on low-boys
and get 'em to my beach?

445
00:24:48,723 --> 00:24:51,292
Sure, if you think you
can use them, you got it.

446
00:24:51,325 --> 00:24:55,129
I'll take care of it. They'll be on
your beach before sundown tomorrow.

447
00:24:55,162 --> 00:24:58,933
- I want them both.
- We're gonna take you over to Ocean Beach,

448
00:24:58,966 --> 00:25:01,166
then out to the Farrallons,
and then we'll get you home.

449
00:25:02,136 --> 00:25:03,771
Don't worry, Charlie.

450
00:25:03,804 --> 00:25:05,940
We got a nice place down here.

451
00:25:05,973 --> 00:25:09,010
Get some oysters and raw clams,

452
00:25:09,043 --> 00:25:11,278
maybe on runny eggs.

453
00:25:14,181 --> 00:25:16,784
( retches, coughs )

454
00:25:31,165 --> 00:25:34,635
Charlie, what kind of shit
are you pulling out here?

455
00:25:34,668 --> 00:25:37,571
- What are you talking about?
- We're not building freeways.

456
00:25:37,605 --> 00:25:39,273
This ain't no tar
and gravel job.

457
00:25:39,306 --> 00:25:42,910
